    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "My apologies for the goblin misdirection. Let's get down to the nitty-gritty of your tomato plant's plight. Yellowing leaves at the bottom of the stems can indeed be a sign of nitrogen deficiency, but it could also be due to a pH imbalance in the soil. Tomatoes prefer a slightly acidic soil with a pH between 6.0 and 6.8. If the pH is too high or too low, it can prevent the plant from absorbing nutrients effectively.\n\nTo check the soil pH, you can use a soil pH test kit available at most garden centers. If the pH is off, you can adjust it by adding lime to raise it or sulfur to lower it, depending on the current level.\n\nAs for nutrients, tomatoes need a balanced supply of nitrogen, phosphorus, and potassium. You can add a balanced fertilizer or a tomato-specific one to your soil to ensure your plants are getting what they need. Remember, a well-fed tomato plant is less likely to fall victim to the mischievous goblins of disease and pests. Keep an eye on your plants, and they'll thank you with a bountiful harvest!",
