      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the patience of a gardener is much like waiting for a goblin to finish his treasure hoard. When you add sulfur or lime to adjust the soil pH, it can take a few weeks to a couple of months for the changes to fully take effect. The plants will gradually show improvement as the pH stabilizes and the soil environment becomes more conducive to nutrient absorption.\n\nTo check if your plants are absorbing nitrogen properly, keep an eye out for the following signs:\n\n1. New Growth: Healthy, dark green leaves and stems are a good indicator that nitrogen is being absorbed well.\n2. Vigorous Growth: If your plants are growing vigorously and producing lush foliage, it's a sign that they're getting enough nitrogen.\n3. Fruit Production: A lack of nitrogen can lead to poor fruit development, so if you're seeing plenty of tomatoes, it's a good sign that nitrogen levels are adequate.\n\nRemember, just like a goblin's treasure, the right balance of nutrients will make your tomato plants thrive. Keep an eye on them, and they'll reward you with a bountiful harvest!",
